-- Hong Kong Stocks Rise; Electricity Producers Gain on Huaneng Power Output
-- Saiyu Zhou
-- 2010-06-23T09:23:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/hong-kong-stocks-fall-for-second-day-liansu-drops-on-debut-tencent-dips.html

          
          
             Hong Kong stocks  rose, reversing a
drop, as power generators gained after Huaneng Group’s daily
power generation reached a record, countering declines in
developers along with lower housing sales in China.  
 China Resources Power Holdings Co., the third-largest Hong
Kong-listed generator, advanced 1.8 percent.  Huaneng Power
International Inc. , the No. 2 mainland electricity producer
listed in Hong Kong by market value, gained 1.4 percent after
Citigroup Inc. recommended investors buy the stock. China
Overseas Land & Investment Ltd., controlled by the nation’s
construction ministry, retreated 2.7 percent.  
 “Positive sentiment is up,” said  Steven Leung , director
of institutional sales at UOB-Kay Hian Ltd. “Investors are
coming back to the market.”  
 The  Hang Seng Index  rose 0.2 percent to 20,856.61, after
falling as much as 0.6 percent and changing directions at least
seven times. The  Hang Seng China Enterprises Index  of Chinese
companies’ so-called H-shares declined 0.3 percent to 12,020.38.  
 The  Hang Seng Index  has dropped 4.6 percent this year as
worries about budget deficits in Europe and credit tightening by
China dented confidence in the strength of the global economy.  
 Shares on the benchmark index are priced at an average  13.8
times  estimated earnings, down from 18 times on Nov. 16, the
highest level in 2009, data compiled by Bloomberg show.  
 China Resources Power advanced 1.8 percent to HK$16.88, the
biggest gain on the Hang Seng Index. Datang International Power
Generation Co., the No. 1 mainland electricity producer listed
in Hong Kong by market value, climbed 1.2 percent to HK$3.40.  
 Huaneng Power Output  
 Huaneng Power  gained 1.4 percent to HK$4.50. Citigroup
raised its recommendation on the stock to “buy” from “hold,”
and increased the share-price estimate to HK$5.50 from HK$5.  
 Parent Huaneng Group’s daily power output reached a record
of 1.53 billion kilowatt-hours on June 19, according to a
statement. That’s a 35 percent gain from a year earlier, it said.  
 Dongfeng Motor Group Co., the partner of PSA Peugeot
Citroen, climbed 1 percent to HK$9.70. Volvo AB aims to expand
its truck unit in China through its venture with Dongfeng, said
Par Ostberg, Volvo Trucks’ Asia president.  
 China Overseas Land retreated 2.7 percent to HK$15.88.
China Resources Land Ltd., a state-controlled developer,
declined 2.3 percent to HK$15.60.  Hang Lung Properties Ltd. ,
which got 40 percent of its fiscal 2009 revenue from China, slid
1.1 percent to HK$30.65.  
 The  Hang Seng Property Index , which dropped 0.5 percent,
was the only one that fell among the four industry groups
tracked by the broader Hang Seng Index.  
 Shanghai housing sales by floor area in the first five
months of the year dropped 32.5 percent from a year earlier to
7.19 million square meters, the Shanghai statistics bureau said.  
 Oil Companies Retreat  
 PetroChina Co. lost 0.7 percent to HK$9.10.  Cnooc Ltd. ,
China’s biggest offshore oil explorer, declined 0.1 percent to
HK$13.78. Crude oil futures retreated 1 percent to $77.85
yesterday.  
 Anhui Conch Cement Co. , China’s biggest cement producer,
dropped 2.1 percent to HK$25.10 after BNP Paribas cut its rating
on the stock to “hold” from “buy.”  
 Techtronic Industries Co., maker of Hoover vacuum cleaners
and Ryobi power tools, dropped 3.6 percent to HK$6.19.  
 Purchases of existing houses in the U.S. decreased 2.2
percent in May to a 5.66 million annual rate, figures from the
National Association of Realtors showed yesterday. Sales were
forecast to rise to a 6.12 million rate, according to the median
forecast of economists in a Bloomberg News survey.  
 China Liansu Group Holdings Ltd. , a producer of plumbing
supplies, was unchanged at HK$2.60 on its debut, after falling
as much as 3.5 percent and climbing as much as 0.8 percent.  
 The company sold 750 million shares at HK$2.60 each,
raising net proceeds of HK$1.82 billion ($234 million) in an
initial share sale, according to a statement.  
 June futures on the Hang Seng Index advanced 0.5 percent to
20,935. Twenty-four stocks gained while 18 fell among the
measure’s 43 constituents.  
